[2
Date: Fri, 21 Apr 2000 10:49:52 -0400
From: Pam Small <PSMALL@niaid.nih.gov>

The prevalence of _S. sonnei_ in developing countries has also caught our
attention. We have worked extensively with all four _Shigella_ species in
the lab. In growing isolates of all four species for making chromosomal
DNA, we have had several lab acquired infections over a period of 15 years.
In all cases infection was due to _S. sonnei_. The second time this
happened we were intrigued enough to conduct some simple experiments to
look at the differential survival of _Shigella_ species in the lab
environment. These experiments suggest that _S. sonnei_ is a hardier
organism than the other three _Shigella_ species. It is more resistant to
desiccation and survives considerably longer on the surface of a lab bench
than other _Shigella_ species. It also can be recovered from petri plates
both a room temperature and 37 degrees C for a much longer time than _S.
flexneri_. This greater hardiness may lead to better survival in the
environment. Thus, even in the presence of good sanitary systems, the
organism may be able to survive under circumstances which would be lethal
for _S. flexneri_.
The _Shigelloides_ hypothesis is also an interesting one. It is likely
though that several factors play a role in the changing epidemiology of
_Shigella_ infections. Are there any examples where there has been a shift
back to _S. flexneri_ after _S. sonnei_ had become established in the
population? Of particular interest would be situations where there has
not been a lapse in good sanitation.
--
P.L.C. Small, Ph.D.
Head, Facultative Intracellular Bacteria Unit
Rocky Mountain Laboratories, NIAID, NIH
904 S. 4th Street
Hamilton, MT. 59840
e-mail: psmall@niaid.nih.gov
