Date: Fri, 21 Apr 2000 16:15:03 -0700
From: Michael C. Samuel <mcsamuel@mindspring.com>

The Foodborne Diseases Active Surveillance Network (FoodNet), part of the
national (U.S.) Emerging Infections Program, conducts active surveillance
for _Shigella_ spp. in 7 sites (CA, CT, GA, MD, MN, NY, and OR). The
predominant species (>97%) in these sites are _S. sonnei_ and _S.
flexneri_. Among all _Shigella_ species reported from 1996 to 1998, where
serotype was indicated, 75.1% were _S. sonnei_ and 22.4% were _S. flexneri_
with no trend by year. There was substantial regional variation, with _S.
flexneri_ representing about 40% of the cases in CA, MD and OR, about 20%
of the cases in CT, MN and NY, and 9% of the cases in GA. These data
suggest that _S. flexneri_ has not disappeared in the western world, or at
least not in some locations, among individuals ill enough to be tested.
Additional FoodNet data can be found at the recently expanded FoodNet site
at: <http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dbmd/foodnet/default.htm>.
For information on possible risk factors for _S. flexneri_ and _S. sonnei_
infection in the San Francisco Bay Area, please see: Baer JT, Vugia DJ,
Reingold AL, Aragon T, Angulo FJ, Bradford WZ. HIV infection as a risk
factor for shigellosis. Emerging Infectious Diseases 1999;5(6):1-5.
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol5no6/pdf/baer.pdf>.
Recent information on the emergence of antimicrobial resistance to
_Shigella_ and the proportion of _S. flexneri_ (40%) in Oregon (and
elsewhere outside the U.S.) can be found at:
<http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/CID/journal/issues/v30n3/990964/990964.html>
--
Alex McNees, M.P.H.
Senior Research Associate &
Michael C. Samuel, Dr.P.H
Medical Epidemiologist
FoodNet - California Emerging Infections Program
e-mail: mcsamuel@mindspring.com
